.SH 9. MULTIPAGE FACILITIES
\f[B]cpdf [\-pad\-before | \-pad\-after] in.pdf\f[R] [<range>]
[\-pad\-with pad.pdf] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Add blank pages before or after each page in the given range.
.TP
\f[B]\-pad\-with\f[R]
Use a separate PDF to act as the padding.
.TP
\f[B]cpdf \-pad\-every <n> in.pdf\f[R] [\-pad\-with pad.pdf] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
Add a blank pages afyer every n pages.
.TP
\f[B]\-pad\-with\f[R]
Use a separate PDF to act as the padding.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf [\-pad\-multiple | \-pad\-multiple\-before]\f[R] [<integer>]
\f[B]in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Add as many blank pages as are required before or after the original
pages to make the file\(cqs length a multiple of the given number of
pages
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-redact\f[R] [\-process\-struct\-trees] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[<range>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Remove the content of the pages in the given range entirely, including
annotations and any resources.
.TP
\f[B]\-process\-struct\-trees\f[R]
Process the document\(cqs structure tree to remove any parts which are
marked as relating to the now\-redacted pages.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf [\-impose <pagesize> | impose\-xy \(lq<x> <y>\(rq]\f[R]
[\-impose\-columns] [\-impose\-rtl] [\-impose\-btt] [\-impose\-margin ]
[\-impose\-spacing <spacing>] [\-impose\-linewidth <width>] [\-fast]
[\-process\-struct\-trees] in.pdf \-o out.pdf
.PP
Cpdf has two imposition operations:
.PP
\f[B]\-impose\f[R] fits multiple pages onto a given page size e.g
\f[B]\-impose a4portrait\f[R] or \f[B]\-impose \(lq8in 12in\(rq\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]\-impose\-xy\f[R] build an output page with the x pages
horizontally and y pages vertically e.g \f[B]\-impose\-xy \(lq2
3\(rq\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-impose\-columns\f[R]
Lay the pages out in columns rather than rows
.TP
\f[B]\-impose\-rtl\f[R]
Lay the pages out right to left
.TP
\f[B]\-impose\-btt\f[R]
Lay the pages out bottom to top
.TP
\f[B]\-impose\-margin\f[R]
Add a margin around the edge of each page.
When using \-impose\-xy the page size increases; with \-impose the pages
are scaled.
.TP
\f[B]\-impose\-spacing\f[R]
Add spacing between rows and columns.
When using \-impose\-xy the page size increases; with \-impose the pages
are scaled.
.TP
\f[B]\-impose\-linewidth\f[R]
Add a border around each input page.
With \-impose the pages are scaled after the border is added, so you
must account for this yourself.
.TP
\f[B]\-process\-struct\-trees\f[R]
Mark the file\(cqs content as an artifact for the purposes of
imposition.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-twoup\-stack\f[R] [\-fast] [\-process\-struct\-trees]
\f[B]in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-twoup\f[R] [\-fast] [\-process\-struct\-trees] \f[B]in.pdf
\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Two old imposition functions which can now both be done with
\f[B]\-impose\f[R] / \f[B]\-impose\-xy\f[R].
The \f[B]\-twoup\-stack\f[R] operation puts two logical pages on each
physical page, rotating them 90 degrees to do so.
The new mediabox is thus larger.
Whereas the \f[B]\-twoup\f[R] operation does the same, but scales the
new sides down so that the media box is unchanged.
.TP
\f[B]\-process\-struct\-trees\f[R]
Mark the file\(cqs content as an artifact for the purposes of
imposition.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-chop \(lq<x> <y>\(rq\f[R] [\-chop\-columns] [\-chop\-rtl]
[\-chop\-btt] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [<range>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
The \f[B]\-chop\f[R] operation cuts up a page into multiple pages,
according to the chosen grid.
.TP
\f[B]\-chop\-columns\f[R]
Arrange by columns instead of rows.
.TP
\f[B]\-chop\-rtl\f[R]
Arrange right to left.
.TP
\f[B]\-chop\-btt\f[R]
Arrange bottom to top.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf [\-chop\-h <y> | \-chop\-v <x>]\f[R] [\-chop\-columns]
\f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [<range>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Chop each page into two, vertically or horizontally, at the given
position.
E.g \f[B]\-chop\-h 200pt\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-chop\-columns\f[R]
Reverse the order of pages in the output.
